🧠 OS Concept 1: Monolithic Kernel vs Microkernel
1️⃣ Simple Idea

A kernel has many services:

process management
memory management
device drivers
file system

Question is:

👉 where should these run?

🔹 Monolithic Kernel

Everything runs inside kernel.

All services inside kernel

Fast ✔
But large and harder to maintain.

Examples:

Linux
UNIX
🔹 Microkernel

Keep only essentials in kernel:

scheduling
memory basics
IPC

Everything else outside.

Safer ✔
Modular ✔

Examples:

Minix
🧠 Analogy

Monolithic:

Whole company in one building.

Microkernel:

Small HQ + departments outside.

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Which is faster?

👉 Monolithic (less communication overhead)

🧠 Memory Trick
Monolithic = big fast
Microkernel = small safe
🧠 OS Concept 2: Busy Waiting vs Blocking
Busy Waiting

Process keeps checking:

Is resource free?
Is resource free?
Is resource free?

CPU wasted ❌

Blocking

Process sleeps until resource available.

CPU free ✔

🧠 Analogy

Busy waiting:

Standing outside washroom checking every second.

Blocking:

Sit down, wait till called.

🔗 Connection

Spinlocks often use busy waiting.

🎯 Placement Trap

Q: Why busy waiting is bad?

👉 Wastes CPU cycles.

🧠 Memory Trick
Busy waiting = active wait
Blocking = passive wait
⚙️ COA Concept 3: Harvard vs Von Neumann Architecture
Von Neumann

One memory for:

data
instructions

Single bus.

(We saw bottleneck yesterday.)

Harvard Architecture

Separate memory for:

instructions
data

Separate buses.

🧠 Analogy

Von Neumann:

One road for cars and trucks.

Harvard:

Two separate roads.

Why Harvard Faster?

Instruction fetch and data access can happen together.

Examples

Many microcontrollers use Harvard-style ideas.

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why Harvard avoids Von Neumann bottleneck?

👉 Separate buses remove competition.

🧠 Memory Trick
Von Neumann = one path
Harvard = two paths
⚙️ COA Concept 4: Cache Write Policies

🔥 Frequently asked

When CPU writes data, what happens to cache and memory?

Two major policies:

1️⃣ Write Through

Update:

Cache
Main memory immediately

✔ Simple
❌ Slower writes

2️⃣ Write Back

Update only cache first.

Memory updated later.

✔ Faster
❌ More complex

🧠 Analogy

Write Through:

Update notebook and final report immediately.

Write Back:

Update notebook first, final report later.

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Which is faster?

👉 Write Back

🧠 Memory Trick
Through = write everywhere now
Back = write memory later
